<h3>Financial Arrangement</h3>

<div class="consequence-text">
<p>You approach the other family with a proposal: you'll pay a larger share of the rent if the other wife can help your wife during her recovery. After some discussion, they agree. You'll now pay $550 per month instead of $400, while they pay $250.</p>

<p>At first, it seems like a good arrangement. The other wife knows what she's doing and helps with the baby, prepares meals, and checks on your wife throughout the day.</p>

<p>But problems quickly emerge.</p>

<p>The two wives have fundamentally different approaches to childcare. Your wife believes in letting the baby cry for short periods to develop independence. The other wife thinks babies should never be left to cry. When your wife tries to explain her approach, the other wife feels criticized.</p>

<p>Then there's the question of responsibility. The other wife agreed to help, but did that include doing all your wife's laundry? Cleaning your side of the apartment? Where does "helping with recovery" end and "being a servant" begin? These questions create tension.</p>

<p>Arguments start. At first they're quiet and tense. Then they become loud enough that both families can hear through the thin walls. The atmosphere in the apartment becomes toxic.</p>

<p>Your wife feels guilty and stressed. The other wife feels taken advantage of. Both families are miserable, and you're paying extra rent for the privilege of this conflict.</p>

<<if $carOwnership === "shared">>
    <p>The conflict escalates until it affects everything you share, including the car. After a particularly heated argument, the other family announces they want to end the car-sharing arrangement.</p>

    <p>"We can't do this anymore," they say. "We'll buy you out of your half when we have the money, but for now, we're taking the car. We need it more - we have more kids to transport."</p>

    <p>You're too exhausted from the conflict to fight about it. The car is gone, just another casualty of this failed arrangement.</p>

